rgency brought about by events unforeseeable for the contracting authority and in accordance with the strict conditions stated in the directive. Coronavirus disease (Covid-19) is a serious infectious respiratory disease, consequences pose a risk to life. The Covid-19 outbreak is a Public Health Emergency of International Concern as declared by the World Health Organisation (WHO) on 30 January 2020 and identified as a pandemic on 11 March 2020. Europe was the centre of the pandemic. The use of personal protective equipment is critical in safeguarding the health and lives of the care professionals treating patients with Covid-19.</P><P>Delays in procuring poses a risk to life and the likelihood of a significantly increased death toll. In March 2020, the NHS experienced severe shortages of PPE, similar shortfalls in PPE stocks were identified globally. There was immense demand for PPE and a procurement following the usual timescales under the Public Contracts Regulations 2015, including accelerated options, was impossible. A delay in engaging with the market by running a usual procurement process ran the risk of failing to acquire the necessary stock of PPE equipment and presenting a significant risk to life.</P><P>Liverpool University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust is satisfied the tests permitting use of the negotiated procedure without prior publication (Regulation 32(2)(c)) were met.</P></D_JUSTIFICATION></PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL><NO_CONTRACT_COVERED_GPA/></PROCEDURE><AWARD_CONTRACT ITEM="1"><CONTRACT_NO>LUH_114</CONTRACT_NO><TITLE><P>Supply of Personal Protective Equipment</P></TITLE><AWARDED_CONTRACT><DATE_CONCLUSION_CONTRACT>2020-03-31</DATE_CONCLUSION_CONTRACT><TENDERS><NB_TENDERS_RECEIVED>1</NB_TENDERS_RECEIVED></TENDERS><CONTRACTORS><NO_AWARDED_TO_GROUP/><CONTRACTOR><ADDRESS_CONTRACTOR><OFFICIALNAME>Jermyn Street Design</OFFICIALNAME><ADDRESS>34 Galena Road, Hammersmith</ADDRESS><TOWN>London</TOWN><POSTAL_CODE>W6 0LT</POSTAL_CODE><COUNTRY VALUE="UK"/><